"center\" class=\"entry colname:col4\" valign=\"middle\">1,624 (100%)  </td></tr></tbody></table><p class=\"attribution author\">Source: Adapted from Raymond A. Mentzer, “Disciplina nervus ecclesiae: The Calvinist Reform of Morals at Nîmes,” <span class=\"formatted_text font_style:italic\">The Sixteenth Century Journal</span>, Vol. 18, No. 1, Spring 1987. </p></div></div>"}],"choicesHtml":["<p class=\"choice_paragraph\">Disputes and quarrels made up approximately half of offenses in both periods, while the percentage of behavioral and ecclesiastical offenses changed significantly.</p>","<p class=\"choice_paragraph\">Disputes and quarrels made up approximately half of offenses in both periods, while the other categories of offenses also showed little change.</p>","<p class=\"choice_paragraph\">Marriage and sexual misconduct offenses remained a majority of the recorded offenses in both periods.</p>","<p class=\"choice_paragraph\">Overall, the number of offenses decreased significantly from the first period to the second period.</p>"],"answer":0}]